expansive logic of capital, and interstate dynamics. Building on and critically extending subaltern and postcolonial perspectives, her study shows how nineteenth-century conceptions of India as a bounded national space and economy bequeathed an enduring tension between a universalistic political economy of nationhood and a nativist project that continues to haunt the present moment. Elegantly conceived and judiciously argued, Producing India will be invaluable to students of history, political economy, geography, and Asian studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNationalismzIndiaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aindia, indian culture, colonialism, colonial influences, economy, economics, nation state, history, east asia studies, postcolonialism, postcolonial, globalism, globalization, cultural study, nationalism, politics, political science, interstate dynamics, capital, 19th century, geography, british occupation, transformation, sovereignty, nationhood, nativism, historical context.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022630508040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226305103423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226305103/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles